                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d861">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/381: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-23T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 23, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1275. Your 1858, September 28. Commercial attaché at Brussels advises in economic
                    trade note no. 59 that shipments from Antwerp are delayed because of strictness
                    with which British authorities are scrutinizing certificates of origin which are
                    required in both transit and domestic goods leaving Belgian ports. Can you
                    reconcile that report with contents of your above-mentioned telegram of
                    September 28.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
